<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-11-22T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-11-22T20:00:00-05:00" n="757" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d757">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A Passenger Travel/42:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-11-22T20:00:00-05:00">November
                                    22, 1939—8 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1433. Your 2799, November 21, 6 p.m. Presidential Proclamation so far
                            limits combat areas to water. Countries bordering on waters described as
                            combat areas are not themselves combat areas.</p>
                        <p>Telegraphic circular instruction regarding validation of passports of
                            Americans in Europe dispatched Berne today.<note n="73" xml:id="d757fn73">
                                <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                            </note> It is believed this circular covers second point your
                            telegram.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>